vocabList.etym: From Middle High German urloup. Related to erlauben. Cognate with English leave (“time off, permission to be away”).
From Middle High German kleidunge, from kleiden (“to clothe”), from kleit, from Old High German *kleid, from Proto-Germanic *klaiþą (“cloth”). Cognate with Dutch kleding, English clothing.
From Middle High German sehen, from Old High German sehan, from Proto-West Germanic *sehwan.

From Middle High German kleit, from Old High German *kleid, from Proto-Germanic *klaiþą, from Proto-Indo-European *gleyt-. Cognate with Dutch kleed, Low German Kleid, English cloth. Possibly related to klettern, Klette, Klei.
From Middle High German schuo, levelled variant of schuoch (inflected schuo(h)-), from Old High German scuoh (“shoe”), from Proto-West Germanic *skōh. More at shoe.
From Middle High German vile, from Old High German filu (“many”), from Proto-West Germanic *felu, from Proto-Germanic *felu, from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₁-. More at fele.
From Middle High German lernen, from Old High German lernēn, lirnēn, from Proto-West Germanic *liʀnēn. Cognate with Old English leornian (Modern English learn). Related to lehren.
From Middle High German vrosch, from Old High German frosk (“frog”), from Proto-West Germanic *frosk (“frog”), from Proto-Germanic *fruskaz (“frog”), from Proto-Indo-European *prew- (“jump, hop”).
From the noun Mal (“time”). Partly shortened from einmal, which is also derived from the noun.
fahren (“drive/ride”) +‎ Rad (“wheel”). Compare Dutch rijwiel.
From Middle High German maht, from Old High German maht. Cognate with Dutch macht, English might.

vocabList.definition: to make, to produce, to create
vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German machen, from Old High German mahhōn, from Proto-West Germanic *makōn, from Proto-Indo-European *mag- (“to knead, mix, make”). Cognate with Dutch maken, Low German maken, English make.

From Middle High German noch, nog, from Old High German noh, from Proto-West Germanic *noh, from Proto-Germanic *nuh, from Proto-Indo-European *nu (“now”) + *-kʷe (“and, also”). Cognate to Dutch nog and noch (which are etymologically the same word).
From Middle High German ieweder, from Old High German ioweder, from io + wedar. Compare English either, Dutch ieder.

From Middle High German gehalt, deverbal from gehalten (“to keep still, retain, preserve, imprison”), itself from halten (“to hold”). The earliest attested sense of the noun is “custody, prison”. In some southern dialects it also means “room, container, closet”. The modern sense develops in the 15th century, at first in the context of coins and metal alloys.

vocabList.definition: chocolate bar, bar of chocolate, candy bar
vocabList.etym: From Schokolade +‎ -n- +‎ Tafel.

vocabList.definition: to donate, to give as charity
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German spenden, from Old High German spentōn (“to consume, use, spend”), from Proto-West Germanic *spendōn (“to spend”).
Borrowed from French passer. Compare English pass.

From Middle High German dāheim, dāheime, darheime, from Old High German dārheime (“at home”), equivalent to da +‎ heim. Compare Middle High German heime (“home, at home”, adverb), Old High German heime, heimi (“home, at home”, adverb).

From Middle High German warumme, war umme, warumbe, war umbe, from Old High German wār umbe. Equivalent to wo (“where”) +‎ um (“in order to, for the purpose of”), thus “for what purpose”. Doublet of  worum, but with the older vocalism preserved. Compare Dutch waarom, which has both meanings.

From Middle High German leiten, from Old High German leiten, from Proto-West Germanic *laidijan, akin to Old English lǣdan (English lead), Old Saxon lēdian, Old Norse leiða. Cognate with English lead.
Inherited from Middle High German gegen, from Old High German gagan, from Proto-West Germanic *gagin, from Proto-Germanic *gagin. Cognate with Dutch tegen, English against, Icelandic gegn.
From Middle High German halten, from Old High German haltan, from Proto-West Germanic *haldan, from Proto-Germanic *haldaną.

From a merger of Middle High German hūfe (hūf), houf (houfe), from Old High German hūfo (more southern) and houf (more northern), from Proto-Germanic *hūpô and its ablaut variant *haupaz, respectively. With the former is cognate Middle Low German hūpe, with the latter Dutch hoop, English heap.
15th century, equivalent to regieren (“to reign”) +‎ -ung.

vocabList.definition: to, towards,Contraction of zu der (“to the (feminine)”).
vocabList.etym: A contraction of zu + der. Compare Dutch ter.
From Middle High German eigenlīche, equivalent to eigen +‎ -lich. Compare Dutch eigenlijk.
By surface analysis, an +‎ fechten.
Sache +‎ -lich. Cognates include Swedish saklig.
From Middle High German ērest, from Old High German ērist, from Proto-West Germanic *airist.
From Middle High German gelegenheit. By surface analysis, gelegen +‎ -heit.
From Middle High German [Term?]. Deverbal from  berufen (literally “calling”).

From Middle High German viur, from Old High German fiur, from Proto-West Germanic *fuir, from Proto-Germanic *fōr, from Proto-Indo-European *péh₂wr̥. Compare Dutch vuur, Low German Füer, West Frisian fjoer, English fire, Danish fyr.
From Middle High German danāch, darnāch, from Old High German daranāh, equivalent to da (“there”) +‎ nach (“after”). Compare Yiddish דערנאָך (dernokh).
From Middle High German losunge equivalent to Los (“lot”) +‎ -ung.

vocabList.definition: entire, whole, complete,strong genitive masculine/neuter singular
to cancel, to call off,first/third-person plural present

vocabList.etym: Compare typologically Latin ēiectāmenta (< ēiectō), Russian отбро́сы (otbrósy) (< отбро́сить (otbrósitʹ)).
From Arbeit +‎ -s- +‎ Schutz.
From Bau +‎ Arbeiter.
bauen (“build”) +‎ Stelle (“place”)

vocabList.definition: eagerly, joyfully, with relish or alacrity
vocabList.etym: alacer +‎ -ter
From vigil.

vocabList.definition: plunder, booty, pillage, spoils of war, property taken in war
vocabList.etym: Likely from the o-grade Proto-Italic *praiɣodā, from (with the prefix *prai-) Proto-Indo-European *gʰed-, whence also the second element in prehendō and probably also hedera.[1]
From Middle High German al-ein. Cognate with Middle English al-one, English alone, Dutch alleen, Low German alleene (Münsterländisch), alläine (Sauerländisch).[1]

vocabList.definition: equal,nominalization of gleich: female equivalent of Gleicher: female equal (female who is equal to another person)
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gelīche, from Old High German gilīkī; equivalent to gleich +‎ -e.
From Middle High German vil līchte (“very easily”), thus: “what could easily happen”. Compare the same in German Low German villicht, Dutch wellicht, Saterland Frisian fielicht.
From da +‎ Mal +‎ -s. Compare Yiddish דעמאָלט (demolt) and דעמאָלטס (demolts).
From Middle High German endelīch (“final”), equivalent to Ende (“end”) +‎ -lich (“-ly”). See English endly.
zu +‎ letzter; cognate with Hunsrik zuletst
nach +‎ her.
neu +‎ -lich

From Middle High German balde, from Old High German baldo, adverb of bald, pald, from Proto-West Germanic *balþ, from Proto-Germanic *balþaz, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰel-. Cognate with Dutch boud, English bold.
Schub (“push”) +‎ Lade (“box”), 16th century.
From Middle High German mēre, from Old High German mēro, from Proto-West Germanic *maiʀō, from Proto-Germanic *maizô, from Proto-Indo-European *mē- (“many”). See English more for more.
Borrowed from Italian soglio.
Inherited from Middle High German lange, an adverb to lanc.
From Middle High German deshalp, from Middle High German des, dez (“from that, therefore, thereon”) + halp (“half”). Cognate to Low German diäßhalw (Paderbornisch).

vocabList.definition:
to propose, to advise in favor of
 to recommend
vocabList.etym: Related to German befehlen (“command, order”), but not fehlen (“to be missing”).
From Middle High German varwe, from Old High German farawa, from Proto-West Germanic *faru, from Proto-Germanic *farwō.

vocabList.definition: to go, to walk,past participle of gehen
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German gegangen, from Old High German gigangan.

vocabList.definition: to go, to walk,first/third-person singular preterite of gehen
vocabList.etym: Etymology 1[edit]
From Middle High German sīt, from Old High German sīd, from Proto-Germanic *sīþuz. Akin to Old Saxon sīd, Old English sīþ. Related to Dutch sedert and sinds.

From Middle High German aber, aver, from Old High German aber, ābar, abur, aver, avur, afur, from Proto-Germanic *aferą (“behind”). Compare Bavarian owa (“but”), Luxembourgish awer (“but”), Saterland Frisian oaber (“but”), Middle Low German āver, German Low German aver (“but”).
From Proto-Finnic *alëk. Cognates include Finnish alle and Veps alle.
From Middle High German al-ein. Cognate with Middle English al-one, English alone, Dutch alleen, Low German alleene (Münsterländisch), alläine (Sauerländisch).[1]

From Old High German andar halb, anderhalb (literally “second half”). Anderthalb is the single surviving relic of an older system to describe fractions, which counted from the higher ordinal number rather than the lower cardinal. Compare Old English ōþer healf, Dutch anderhalf, Danish halvanden. Compare also the use of the word halb in the sense of a half-hour before the following hour, such as halb zwei to mean one thirty. The word anderer has since lost the meaning "second", being used solely as "other" in modern German.
From Middle High German anevāhen, from Old High German anafāhan, from Proto-West Germanic *anafą̄han. Equivalent to an- +‎ fangen.

From Middle High German antwürte, from Old High German antwurti, from Proto-Germanic *andawurdiją. The gender change from neuter to feminine is due to semantic association with Frage (“question”). See also antworten. Cognate to Dutch antwoord and Afrikaans antwoord.
From Middle High German antwürten, from Old High German antwurten, from Proto-Germanic *andawurdijaną. By surface analysis, Antwort +‎ -en.
From Middle High German art, from Old High German *art, from Proto-West Germanic *ard, from Proto-Germanic *ardiz.

From Middle High German ouch, from Old High German ouh, from Proto-Germanic *auk. Cognate with Dutch ook (“also”), Low German ook (“also”), West Frisian ek (“also, too”), Luxembourgish och (“also”), Swedish och (“and”), Icelandic og (“and”), Danish og (“and”), and archaic English eke (“also”).

From Middle High German ougenblick (“quick glance”), corresponding to Auge (“eye”) +‎ -n- +‎ Blick (“glance”). Cognate to Yiddish אויגנבליק (oygnblik), Luxembourgish Abléck, Dutch ogenblik, Danish øjeblik, Swedish ögonblick, Norwegian øyeblikk, Icelandic augnablik. Compare English eyeblink.
From Middle High German ūȥer, from Old High German ūȥar. More at aus. Cf. English outer, Norwegian uten-, ytre.

From Middle High German beginnen, from Old High German biginnan, from Proto-West Germanic *biginnan, from Proto-Germanic *biginnaną. Cognate with Low German beginnen, Dutch beginnen, West Frisian begjinne, and English begin.

From Middle High German behalten, from Old High German bihaltan, from Proto-West Germanic *bihaldan. Equivalent to be- +‎ halten. Cognates include Saterland Frisian behoolde (“to keep”), Dutch behouden (“to keep, restrain, preserve”), English behold, Danish and Norwegian beholde (“to keep”) and Swedish behålla (“to keep”).
From Middle High German behandeln (“to touch with the hand”), equivalent to be- +‎ handeln. Compare Saterland Frisian behondelje, Dutch behandelen, English behandle.
behandeln +‎ -ung
From Middle High German beide, bēde, from Old High German beide, bēde, from Proto-Germanic *bai.

From Middle High German bīspil, bīspel, from Old High German bīspel (“proverb", "example”), equivalent to bī- (“by-”) + spel (“talk”), the latter from Proto-Germanic *spellą (“news, message, tale”). Cognate with Old English bīspel (“proverb", "example”), English byspel (“example”). Unrelated to spielen (“to play”).

From Middle High German bekomen, from Old High German biqueman, bikweman, from Proto-West Germanic *bikweman, from Proto-Germanic *bikwemaną, equivalent to be- +‎ kommen. Cognate to Dutch bekomen, English become.

From Middle High German bemerken, from Old High German bimerken, from Proto-West Germanic *bimarkijan. Equivalent to be- +‎ merken. Cognate with Dutch bemerken, also related to Middle Dutch and Middle High German bemarken, and English bemark.
be- +‎ nutzen

From Middle High German bequæme, bekōme (“suitable”), from Old High German biquāmi, derived from biqueman (whence German bekommen). The word seems originally to have been more common in Central and Low German; therefore possibly reinforced by cognate Middle Low German bequēme. The consonantism -qu-, which generally remained more stable in the north than it did in Upper German, may also point to that. Further cognate with Dutch bekwaam, English queem, queme, Swedish bekväm.

From Middle High German besitzen, from Old High German bisizzen, from Proto-West Germanic *bisittjan, from Proto-Germanic *bisitjaną, Equivalent to be- +‎ sitzen. Cognate with Norwegian Bokmål besitte, Danish besidde, Dutch bezitten, English besit, Swedish besitta, Gothic 𐌱𐌹𐍃𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽 (bisitan).
From besonder (“special”, adjective) +‎ -s.
From Middle High German beȥȥer, from Old High German beȥȥiro, from Proto-West Germanic *batiʀō, from Proto-Germanic *batizô.

From Middle High German besprechen, from Old High German besprechan, besprehhan (also bisprechōn, bisprehhōn), from Proto-Germanic *bisprekaną (“to speak about, discuss, blame”), equivalent to be- +‎ sprechen. Cognate with English bespeak, Dutch bespreken, West Frisian besprekke.

The adjective is from Middle High German eben, from Old High German eban, the adverb from ebano; from Proto-West Germanic *ebn, from Proto-Germanic *ebnaz and its adverb equivalent. Cognate with Low German even, Dutch even, effen, English even, Danish jævn.
eben +‎ so. Compare English even so.
ehemals +‎ -ig

From Middle High German eigen, from Old High German eigan, from Proto-West Germanic *aigan, from Proto-Germanic *aiganaz, the past participle of Proto-Germanic *aiganą. Cognate with Dutch eigen, English own.

The combined form einander does not inflect in modern German, and may be used unchanged in dative and accusative grammatical cases. Older forms could show inflection on the second ander portion, or on both the ein and ander portions. Any prepositions, which grammatically and semantically would apply to the second ander portion of the word, were already appearing in front of the compound term in Old High German, and in New High German (i.e., modern German), prepositions are compounded onto the front of the term.[1]
See the etymology of the corresponding lemma form.
ein- (“into”) +‎ verstanden (past participle of verstehen “to understand”)
Inherited from Middle High German ende, from Old High German enti, from Proto-West Germanic *andī, from Proto-Germanic *andijaz, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂entíos.
From Middle High German enge, from Old High German engi, from Proto-West Germanic *angī.
From Middle High German erkennen, from Old High German irkennen, from Proto-West Germanic *uʀkannijan. Equivalent to er- +‎ kennen.
From Middle High German valsche, valsch, from Old High German *falski, from Proto-West Germanic *falskī (“false, counterfeit”).
From Old High German fasto, compare fest. Cognate with English adverb fast. Compare Dutch vast.
From Middle High German vælen, velen, valen, from Old French faillir, from Latin fallō. Cognate with English fail.
From fehlen in the sense of “to fail”.
From Middle High German fertec, from Old High German fartīg, from the noun fart (“journey”). Cognate with Dutch vaardig, Low German fardig, Old English fierd (“expedition, campaign”).

From Middle High German vinden, from Old High German findan, from Proto-West Germanic *finþan, from Proto-Germanic *finþaną. Cognate with Bavarian findn, Low German finden, Dutch vinden, English find, Danish finde.
From Middle High German volgen, from Old High German folgēn, from Proto-West Germanic *folgēn, from Proto-Germanic *fulgāną. Doublet of  followen.

Cognate with Saterland Frisian fräigje (“to ask”), Dutch vragen (“to ask”), Low German fragen (“to ask”), English frain (“to ask, inquire”), Swedish fråga (“to ask”), Icelandic fregna (“to hear of, learn about”).

From Middle High German genoue, genouwe, geneuwe (“narrow, close, exact”), from ge- + nou(we) (“narrow, close, exact”), from Old High German *hnouw (“narrow, close”), from Proto-Germanic *hnawwaz. Cognate with Middle Low German nouwe, nau (“narrow, brief, exact”), Dutch nauw (“narrow, close”), Old English hnēaw (“niggardly, miserly, stingy”), Old Norse hnøggr (“niggardly, stingy, scant”). More at niggardly.

Cognate with Dutch genoeg, Low German (ge)noog, English enough, West Frisian genôch, Danish nok, Swedish nog. Further Indo-European cognates: Latin nancīscor (“to get, to obtain”), Slovene nesti (“to carry”), Albanian kënaq (“to satisfy”).

From Middle High German gërne, from Old High German gërno, from Proto-West Germanic *gernō, from Proto-Germanic *gernô (“willingly, gladly”), an adverbial form of *gernaz (“eager, willing”). Akin to German Low German geren (Paderbornisch), Dutch gaarne, English yern, Swedish gärna, Danish gerne.
Cognate with Bavarian glaubn, glabn, Dutch geloven, Low German glöven, Gothic 𐌲𐌰𐌻𐌰𐌿𐌱𐌾𐌰𐌽 (galaubjan). Also related with English believe, which see.
From Middle High German got, from Old High German got, from Proto-West Germanic *god, from Proto-Germanic *gudą. Compare Dutch god, English god, Danish gud, Gothic 𐌲𐌿𐌸 (guþ).
Borrowed from Latin grātulārī.
Cognate with West Frisian grûn, Dutch grond, English ground. Non-Germanic cognates include Albanian grundë (“brittle earth”) and gryej (“to erode, crumble”).[1]
Inherited from Middle High German guot, from Old High German guot, from Proto-West Germanic *gōd, from Proto-Germanic *gōdaz, from Proto-Indo-European *gʰedʰ- (“to unite, be associated, suit”).
Short for ich wünsche einen guten Tag! (“I wish [you] a good day!”), hence the accusative form of the adjective. Compare Yiddish אַ גוטן טאָג (a gutn tog).

From Middle High German haben, from Old High German habēn (akin to Old Saxon hebbian, Old Norse hafa (Swedish hava/ha), Old Frisian habba, Gothic 𐌷𐌰𐌱𐌰𐌽 (haban), Old English habban), from Proto-West Germanic *habbjan, from Proto-Germanic *habjaną, from Proto-Indo-European *keh₂p- (“to grasp”). Cognates include Bavarian håbn, Yiddish האָבן (hobn), Dutch hebben, English have, Danish have.
From Middle High German halp, from Old High German halb, from Proto-West Germanic *halb, from Proto-Germanic *halbaz. Compare Dutch half, English half, Danish halv.
From Middle High German halten, from Old High German haltan, from Proto-West Germanic *haldan, from Proto-Germanic *haldaną.

The predominant form in Middle High German and throughout modern dialects of High German is hie (and variants) with loss of the final -r. The form hier began to gain ground from the late 16th century (in spite of Luther’s usage), which may point to influence by cognate Middle Low German hīr, hēr (where no r-less form seems to exist; but compare modern Limburgish heej).

From Middle High German hoffen (12th c.), from northern Old High German *hoffōn, from Proto-West Germanic *hopōn. It is uncertain whether the (unattested but probable) Old High German form was inherited or rather borrowed from Old Dutch hopon with implementation of the High German consonantism (which was then still entirely predictable). In fact, some scholars consider that all continental forms go back to Old English hopian, introduced as a religious term by Anglo-Saxon missionaries. The word was at any rate absent from Upper German, where it only established itself in later Middle High German, gradually displacing the now obsolete gedingen. See English hope for more.
Borrowed from French idée, from Latin idea (“a (Platonic) idea; archetype”), from Ancient Greek ἰδέα (idéa, “notion, pattern”), from εἴδω (eídō, “I see”).
From the verb einbegreifen.
irgend (“any; at all”) +‎ wo (“where”)
From Middle High German ja, from Old High German ja, jā (“yes”), from Proto-Germanic *ja (“yes”).
From Middle High German ieweder, from Old High German ioweder, from io + wedar. Compare English either, Dutch ieder.
From Middle High German jeman, ieman, iemant, from Old High German ioman, eoman, equivalent to je +‎ man.
From Middle High German jener, from Old High German jenēr, from Proto-West Germanic *jain, from Proto-Germanic *jainaz. Cognate with English yon.
From Middle High German iez, ieze, iezū, iezō, iezuo, from Old High German iozuo (“straightaway, at once; further”), equivalent to je +‎ zu. Compare English yet, Yiddish יעצט (yetst).

17th century, from French être capot (“not having won any trick in a card game”, as in German schwarz sein). The further origin is uncertain, though it probably stems from a figurative usage of capot (“hood”); Pfeiffer suggests an image of "a hood pulled over one's head and face" > "restrained and unable to perform actions" (DWDS). Compare Dutch kapot.

From Middle High German kein; from the merger of dechein/dehein (“someone; anyone”), from Old High German dehein; and nechein/nehein (“not any”), from Old High German nihein. Compare Dutch geen, Yiddish קיין (keyn). More at none.
From Middle High German klār, clār, formally from Middle Low German klār or Middle Dutch claer and reinforced by Old French cler, both from Latin clārus (“bright”).[1]
From Middle High German kriegen (“to war, to conquer property or land”). Verbalisation of Krieg (“war”). Cognate to Bavarian kriagn, Dutch krijgen, Hunsrik krien.
From Middle High German lanc, from Old High German lang, from Proto-West Germanic *lang, from Proto-Germanic *langaz.
Inherited from Middle High German lange, an adverb to lanc.
From Middle High German lancsam, from Old High German lancsam, from Proto-West Germanic *langasam (“lengthy, long-lasting”), equivalent to lang +‎ -sam.

From Middle High German lāȥen, from Old High German lāȥan, from Proto-West Germanic *lātan (“to let, allow”), from Proto-Germanic *lētaną (“to leave behind, allow”), from Proto-Indo-European *leh₁d- (“to let, leave behind”). Cognates include Bavarian låssn, Dutch laten, English let.
From Middle High German leider, from Old High German leidir, equivalent to the comparative form of leid.

vocabList.definition: to make, to produce, to create
vocabList.etym: Inherited from Middle High German machen, from Old High German mahhōn, from Proto-West Germanic *makōn, from Proto-Indo-European *mag- (“to knead, mix, make”). Cognate with Dutch maken, Low German maken, English make.
From Middle High German mēre, from Old High German mēro, from Proto-West Germanic *maiʀō, from Proto-Germanic *maizô, from Proto-Indo-European *mē- (“many”). See English more for more.
Derived from mehr (“more”).
From Middle High German meinunge, from Old High German meinunga. By surface analysis, meinen +‎ -ung. Compare Dutch mening and English meaning.
Inherited from Middle High German nëmen, from Old High German nëman, from Proto-West Germanic *neman, from Proto-Germanic *nemaną, from Proto-Indo-European *nem- (“to give or take ones due”).
From Middle High German nein, from a contraction of Old High German ni ein. Compare Old English nān, from ne ān (Modern English none, further contracted to no).
Compare Dutch nieuw, English new, Danish ny, Gothic 𐌽𐌹𐌿𐌾𐌹𐍃 (niujis).
From Middle High German niwiht, niweht, niht, a contracted form of Old High German niowiht, from nio (“never”) + wiht (“being, creature”), the last from Proto-Germanic *wihtą.
From Middle High German nihtes niht (“nothing of nothing”), a reenforcing construction with niht. See nicht.[1] Cognate with Dutch niets, Low German nix, Hunsrik nichs.

From Middle High German nieman, from Old High German nioman; equivalent to nie (“never”) + Mann (“man”). Cognate with Dutch niemand, Afrikaans niemand, Low German nemann, nemand, nümand, Hunsrik nimmand.
From earlier Numero, from Italian numero, from Latin numerus (“number”). The feminine gender is probably due to the influence of Zahl (“number”).
From late Middle High German nuor, contracted from older niwer, newære, from Old High German niwāri, ni wāri (“were it not”). Cognate with Yiddish נאָר (nor), Dutch maar, Old English nǣre.
From Middle High German oder, from Old High German odar. Related to Old English oþþe, Middle Dutch oder, Yiddish אָדער (oder).

From Middle High German offen, Old High German offan, ofan, ophan, from Proto-West Germanic *opan. Cognate with Low German open, apen, Dutch open, English open, Danish åben, Swedish öppen. Related to auf.
From Middle High German ofte, oft, uft, from Old High German ofta, ofto, oftu, from Proto-Germanic *ufta, *uftō (“often”). Cognate with Dutch oft, English oft and often.
From Middle High German āne (“without”), from Old High German āna, ānu, āno (“without”), from Proto-Germanic *ēnu, *ēnō (“without”), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁(n̥)new.
Borrowed from Latin prō (“for”).
Borrowed from Italian per cento, from Latin per (“through, by”) and centum (“hundred”), modified by the influence of Latin pro (“for”) or German pro.
Deverbal from  quatschen.

From Middle High German ruofen, from Old High German ruofan, hruofan, from Proto-West Germanic *hrōpan, from Proto-Germanic *hrōpaną. Cognate with Dutch roepen, English roop, which see. Alongside there existed a weak Middle High German ruofen, from Old High German (h)ruofen. Weak conjugation is attestable until the 19th century. It indirectly lingers in the umlautless present forms, as against obsolete du rüfst, er rüft. (Lack of umlaut on rounded diphthong before labial is regular in Upper German, but it has only established itself here, not in laufen and saufen.)
From Middle High German runt, from Old French ront, from Latin rotundus (“round”) from rota (“wheel, disk”).
From Middle High German sagen, from Old High German sagēn, from Proto-West Germanic *saggjan, from Proto-Germanic *sagjaną, ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *sekʷ-.

From earlier slecht, from Middle High German sleht, from Old High German sleht (see also schlicht), from Proto-Germanic *slihtaz. Cognate with English slight, Dutch slecht, Afrikaans sleg, Icelandic sléttur, Faroese slættur, Swedish slätt, Danish slet , Gothic 𐍃𐌻𐌰𐌹𐌷𐍄𐍃 (slaihts), and Norwegian slett.
schließen +‎ -lich

From earlier slim, from Middle High German slimp (“slanting, awry”), from Old High German slimb, from Proto-West Germanic *slimb, from Proto-Germanic *slimbaz (“oblique, crooked”). Compare English slim (“thin”), Dutch slim (“clever, smart”), Middle Dutch slim (“bad, crooked”).
Schreck +‎ -lich; from Late Middle High German [Term?].
From Middle High German schrien, from Old High German scrian, ultimately from Proto-West Germanic *skrīan. Compare English scream.[1]
From Middle High German sēr, from Old High German sēr (“sored, injured”), from Proto-West Germanic *sair.

Inherited from Middle High German sīn, from Old High German sīn (“to be”) (suppleted with Proto-Germanic *wesaną (“to be”) and *beuną (“to be, exist, become”)), from Proto-Indo-European *h₁es- (“to be, exist”). Cognate with Dutch zijn (“to be”), Low German sien (“to be”).
seit +‎ dem
Borrowed from Latin secunda. The units of time and angle are from pars minuta secunda (literally “second minute part”).
From Middle High German siher, from Old High German sihur, from Proto-West Germanic *sikur (“secure, sure”), from Latin sēcūrus (“worryless; carefree; secure”).
From so +‎ gar.

From Middle High German sunst, sust, sus, from Old High German sus (“thus”), from Proto-West Germanic *sus, from *swā (“so”), formally related to Proto-West Germanic *þus (“thus”). Cognate with Hunsrik sunst, Old Saxon sus (Middle Low German süs),[1] archaic Dutch zonst (“otherwise”), Alemannic German sus and suscht.

From Middle High German tuon, from Old High German tuon, from Proto-West Germanic *dōn, from Proto-Germanic *dōną, derived from Proto-Indo-European *dʰeh₁- (“to put, set, place”). Cognate with English do.

From late Middle High German ūre, from Middle Low German ûre (“hour”), from Middle Dutch ure, from Old Dutch *ūra, from Old French houre, from Latin hōra, from Ancient Greek ὥρα (hṓra), from Proto-Indo-European *yeh₁- (“year, season”). The word was borrowed in the late 14th century when the diphthongization of -ū- into -ou-, -au- was already complete in most dialects; a shifted form exists, however, in dialects (compare Luxembourgish Auer). In German, the word early on developed the sense “timing device”, not present in other languages. Compare further Dutch uur, English hour, French heure. Doublet of  Jahr.
From Middle High German unde, from Old High German unti, from Proto-Germanic *andi, *anþi, from Proto-Indo-European *h₂énti. Compare Dutch en, English and, Danish end.
From verscheiden in its original sense of "separate, leave".
From Middle High German vile, from Old High German filu (“many”), from Proto-West Germanic *felu, from Proto-Germanic *felu, from Proto-Indo-European *pleh₁-. More at fele.
From Middle High German vil līchte (“very easily”), thus: “what could easily happen”. Compare the same in German Low German villicht, Dutch wellicht, Saterland Frisian fielicht.
From Old High German fiorteil. Equivalent to vier +‎ Teil.
.mw-parser-output .etytree{width:max-content;max-width:100%;overflow:hidden;box-sizing:border-box}

From Middle High German wëhseln, from Old High German *wehsalōn, from Proto-Germanic *wihslōną, from Proto-Indo-European *weyk-, *weyḱ- (“to change”). Compare Dutch wisselen, Luxembourgish wiesselen, dialectal English wissle, more distantly Latin vicis, English week, German Woche.
From the accusative of Middle High German wīle (modern Weile), from Old High German wīla, from Proto-West Germanic *hwīlu, from Proto-Germanic *hwīlō.
From Middle High German wanne, wenne, from Old High German hwanne, hwenne, from Proto-West Germanic *hwan, similar to the adverb wann.

From Middle High German wërden, from Old High German werdan, from Proto-West Germanic *werþan, from Proto-Germanic *werþaną. Cognate with Dutch worden, obsolete English worth, Swedish varda, Norwegian Nynorsk verta, and also with Latin vertō (“to turn”).

From the same root as Gewicht (“weight”) + -ig (“-y”), thus pertaining to wiegen (“to weigh”). See also gewichtig, a (formal or elevated) synonym of wichtig. Weight is often used as a metaphor for importance;
compare German schwerwiegend (“serious, grave”), as well as English weighty, heavy.

From Middle High German wie, a merger of two interrelated forms: 1.) Old High German hwio, from older hwēo, from Proto-Germanic *hwaiwa; cognate with Gothic 𐍈𐌰𐌹𐍅𐌰 (ƕaiwa). 2.) Old High German hwē, hwie, from Proto-Germanic *hwē; cognate with Gothic 𐍈𐌴 (ƕē). The latter is a variant of Proto-Germanic *hwī, whence English why, and is further a fossilized instrumental case of *hwaz, *hwat (“who, what”). Form 1 is also related to this stem. Outside of High German the only direct modern cognate is Limburgish wie.
From Middle High German wider, whence English widdershins via Middle Low German borrowing; from Old High German widar, from Proto-West Germanic *wiþr (“toward, against”). Cognate with English wither.
wieder- +‎ holen

Inherited from Middle High German willekomen, from Old High German willechomen, from Proto-Germanic *wiljakumô. Cognate to Dutch welkom, English welcome, Danish velkommen, and other Germanic forms. Cognate with Portuguese bem-vindo, French bienvenu, Italian benvenuto, Spanish bienvenido, possibly Germanic calques.
From wirk(en) +‎ -lich. Cognate with Bavarian wirkli, wirkle, Hunsrik werklich and Dutch werkelijk.
From Middle High German wullīn, wüllīn, from Old High German wullīn, from Proto-Germanic *wullīnaz (“woolen”), equivalent to Wolle +‎ -en.

From Middle High German wunderbære (also wunderberen, wunderberende), equivalent to Wunder +‎ -bar. Akin to German Low German wunnerbaar, Low German wunnerbor, Dutch wonderbaar, Saterland Frisian wunderboar, and also calques Danish, Norwegian Bokmål and Swedish underbar.

From Middle High German wunsch, from Old High German wunsc, from Proto-Germanic *wunskō, from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to wish, love”). Compare Dutch wens, English wish, West Frisian winsk, Danish ønske.

From Middle High German zāle, from Old High German zala, from Proto-West Germanic *talu, from Proto-Germanic *talō, from Proto-Indo-European *dol- (“reckoning, calculation, fraud”), from Proto-Indo-European *del- (“to reckon, calculate”), cognate with Danish tale, Dutch taal, Low German Tahl, Hunsrik Zaal, English tale.

Cognate with Low German tehn, Gothic 𐍄𐌹𐌿𐌷𐌰𐌽 (tiuhan), Middle Dutch tīen, Old English tēon, Old Norse toga, West Frisian tsjen. Compare obsolete English tee (“to draw, lead, proceed”) and from the same root as English tie.
From Middle High German zil, from Old High German zil, from Proto-West Germanic *til, from Proto-Germanic *tilą. Cognate to Old English til.
From Old High German zimilīh (“befitting”) or possibly directly from ziemen +‎ -lich.

A distinction between both words has widely been retained in dialects, and also to some degree in modern spoken German (see pronunciation section below). Cognate with Silesian East Central German zu (contractions with the definite article: zum m or n, zur f); Dutch te, toe; Old Saxon tō; English to, too.
Univerbation of zu +‎ Frieden, 16th c. Compare Dutch tevreden.
From Middle High German zuomachen, zuo machen, zūmachen, equivalent to zu- +‎ machen. Compare Middle Low German tômaken, whence German Low German tomaken.

Dutch tezamen (“together”) has been formed in a similar fashion, with its contracted form being samen and its ancestral form tsamen. Also cognate with Scots samin (“together”), Danish sammen (“together”), Swedish samman (“together”).
Attested since the 17th century, nominalization of absehen[1]
From Middle High German ahtunge (“consideration, appreciation”), from Old High German ahtunga, from Proto-West Germanic *ahtungu. By surface analysis, achten +‎ -ung.
Cognate with Middle Low German ānen (whence German Low German ahnen (“to suspect, guess”)), dialectal Dutch anen (“to conjecture, tell, calculate”), Saterland Frisian oanje (“to suspect, guess”).
ahnen +‎ -ung

vocabList.definition: to imply, to mean, to signify, to indicate, to spell, to betoken
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German bediuten, betiuten, from Old High German bidiuten. Equivalent to be- +‎ deuten.
From da +‎ mit. Compare English theremid, therewith.

From Middle High German erlouben, from Old High German irlouben, arlouben, from Proto-West Germanic *uʀlaubijan, from Proto-Germanic *uzlaubijaną. Cognate with Old English ālīefan, ālȳfan (“to allow”). More at leave (“permission”).
From Middle High German volge, from Old High German folga, from Proto-West Germanic *folgēn.
From Middle High German geschehen, geschēn, geschegen, from Old High German giskehan, scehan, from Proto-West Germanic *skehan (“to spring, come up, emerge, happen”). Cognate to Dutch geschieden.
Univerbation of heute +‎ zu +‎ Tage.
Univerbation of ins (“in the”) +‎ gesamt (“total”)

From Middle High German kūme, from Old High German kūmo, from Proto-Germanic *kūmaz, *kūmijaz (“weak, pitiful, frail”), from Proto-Indo-European *gewH- (“to call, cry”).[1] Cognate with English comely and archaic Dutch kuim (“barely”).
From Middle High German obe, ob, from Proto-Germanic *jabai (“when, if”). Compare English if.
From anstatt (“instead of”).
um +‎ sonst, compare Danish omsonst.
Literally, “before everything”.

From Middle High German wāgen, ultimately from from Old High German wāga (“scales, balance; weight”) (see Waage), in the sense of putting something on the scales, not knowing where the balance will fall.

From Middle High German zwāre, contraction of ze wāre (“verily, indeed”), from Old High German zi wāre (8th c.). Equivalent to zu + wahr.[1] The concessive use developed first in cognate Middle Low German twâre. Compare Czech sice.
ab- +‎ trocknen
From Middle High German abewaschen, from Old High German abawaskan. Equivalent to ab- +‎ waschen.
From Middle High German anemachen. Equivalent to an- +‎ machen.
auf- +‎ stehen
auf- (“up”) +‎ wachen (“to be awake”)
From Middle High German ūzsehen. Analysable as aus- (“out”) +‎ sehen (“to see”). Compare Yiddish אויסזען (oyszen), Dutch uitzien, Norwegian Nynorsk sjå ut, Swedish se ut, Danish se ud.

The two verbs early on were blended to some degree, each developing both weak and strong forms. Bachen was originally the predominant form in Upper German. Backen prevailed in the modern standard language because it was common in Central German and also in line with Middle Low German backen (where *baken is not attested). Cognate with German Low German backen, Dutch bakken, English bake, Danish bage, Swedish baka, and also Ancient Greek φώγω (phṓgō).
be- +‎ schreiben

From Middle High German buochstabe, from Old High German *buohstabo (“letter, writing”) (attested only as Old High German buohstab; > German Buchstab), from Proto-West Germanic *bōkstabō, from Proto-Germanic *bōkstabô, a variant of *bōkstabaz.[1] Compare English bookstaff, bookstave.
From Buchstabe (“letter”) +‎ -ieren (“-ise, -ify”).
From Old High German decchen, from Proto-Germanic *þakjaną. Equivalent to Dach +‎ -en. Cognate with West Frisian dekke, Dutch dekken, English thatch, Danish tække, Swedish täcka.
From Middle High German īnslāfen. Equivalent to ein- +‎ schlafen.
From Middle High German keren, kern, from Old High German kerian, kerien, from Proto-Germanic *karjaną.
From Middle High German lēr, lēre, lǣre, from Old High German lāri, from Proto-West Germanic *lāʀi, from Proto-Germanic *lēziz. Cognate with Bavarian lar, Dutch laar, English leer.
Etymology 1[edit]
Compare English lay, Danish lægge.

From Middle High German liebe (“joy, affection, kindliness”), from Old High German liob, lioba (“fortune, health, pleasantness, joy”), from Proto-West Germanic *leubu (“love”). Related with Old High German luba, English love (from Proto-Germanic *lubō).

The singularly attested Old High German liobōn (“to love”) probably remained without continuation; the modern sense was derived in late Middle High German from the noun liebe (“love”) on the model of minnen (“to love”), from minne, which had developed a sexual overtone. It remained absent from most traditional dialects, which use variants of lieb haben or gern haben instead (compare the usage note below). Related to English love. Compare Dutch lieven.
Compare Low German liggen, Dutch liggen, English lie, Danish ligge, Gothic 𐌻𐌹𐌲𐌰𐌽 (ligan).
From French organiser +‎ -ieren. Cognate with Hunsrik organiseere.
Perhaps related to Latin puto in the sense of "clean".
From Middle High German slāfen, from Old High German slāfan, from Proto-West Germanic *slāpan. Compare Low German slapen, Dutch slapen, English sleep.

Cognate with Dutch snijden (“to cut, carve, intersect”), Low German snieden (“to cut”), dialectal English snithe (“to cut”) (related to snide), Swedish snida (“to carve, engrave”), Icelandic sníða (“to trim, tailor”).
From Middle High German stecken, from Old High German steckōn, a geminated derivative of stehhan, whence modern stechen.

Past forms are inherited from Old High German stuond, stuonden, etc. These are themselves suppletive of Proto-West Germanic *standan's past forms in *stōnd-, replacing former forms inherited from *stān in *stōþ-. Compare english stood. Their a-vocalism is due to analogy with other strong verbs such as binden (band) and finden (fand), dating back to Middle High German. See also stand.
From Middle High German stellen, from Old High German stellen, from Proto-West Germanic *stalljan (“to put, position”), from Proto-Indo-European *stel- (“to place, put, post, stand”).

From Middle High German teil, Old High German teil, from Proto-West Germanic *daili, akin to Old Saxon dēl, cognate with English deal, Dutch deel, Low German Deil, Swedish del, Norwegian Bokmål del, Norwegian Nynorsk del, Danish del. Doublet of  Deal.
From Middle High German and Old High German teilen, from Proto-West Germanic *dailijan (“to divide, part, deal”). Cognate with English deal.

The form trucken was originally predominant, but the word eventually became standardized in an old western variant with -o-. Cognate with Old Saxon drokno (“dry”, adverb), Old English ġedrycnan (“to dry up”).
Deadjectival verb from trocken (“dry (adj.)”), i.e. trocken +‎ -en
vor- +‎ bereiten
From Middle High German wecken, from Old High German wecchen, from Proto-West Germanic *wakkjan (“to wake up, to awaken”).

The original e-form is preserved in the doublet  wägen, which is now chiefly restricted to figurative senses and derivatives (abwägen, erwägen). Moreover, bewegen is partly from the same verb, partly from the causative (Proto-Germanic *wagjaną).
zu- +‎ nehmen
Unadapted borrowing from French adresse.
From Middle High German alter, from Old High German altar, from Proto-Germanic *aldrą. Cognate with German Low German Oller.

From Middle High German bart, from Old High German bart, from Proto-West Germanic *bard, from Proto-Germanic *bardaz, from Proto-Indo-European *bʰardʰeh₂. Compare Dutch baard, Luxembourgish Baart, West Frisian burd, English beard.
Meaning 3 ("toilet seat") is derived in analogy with the usually round shape of spectacle frames surrounding the glass, just as a toilet seat surrounds the toilet hole.
Familie +‎ -n- +‎ Name
From Middle High German geboren, from Old High German giboran

First attested in the 11th century. From Middle High German heimuote, heimüete, from Old High German heimōti, heimuoti, from Proto-West Germanic *haimōdī (“homeland”). Compare Bavarian Hoamat, Silesian East Central German Heemte.
From Middle High German hīrāten, which is derived from Middle High German hīrāt (“marriage”), whence German Heirat (“marriage”).
From Middle High German heiȥen, from Old High German heiȥan, from Proto-West Germanic *haitan, from Proto-Germanic *haitaną.
From Middle High German lëdic, lëdec, from Old High German *lidig, from Proto-Germanic *liþugaz.

From Middle High German versprechen (“to guarantee”), from Old High German firsprehhan (“to defend verbally, to warrant”), from Proto-West Germanic *frasprekan. Analyzable as ver- +‎ sprechen. The sense “to misspeak” is a later transparent derivation (see the prefix).
vor- +‎ Name

an +‎ genehm, from Old High German nami,[1] ultimately from the same root as nehmen. Compare Sanskrit नमस्ते (namaste, “salutations (to you)”) for similar semantic development from the same Proto-Indo-European root.
Compare Low German dick, Dutch dik, English thick, Danish tyk.
From German Low German doof (“deaf”), from Middle Low German dôf, from Old Saxon dof, from Proto-West Germanic *daub. Cognate to Upper German taub.
Inherited from Middle High German ērlich, from Old High German ērlīh, from Proto-West Germanic *aiʀulīk. Equivalent to Ehre (“honour”) +‎ -lich (“-ly”).
From Middle High German ërnst, from Old High German ernust, from Proto-West Germanic *ernust, from Proto-Germanic *ernustuz, whence also English earnest.
Fleiß +‎ -ig
From Middle High German vrech, from Old High German freh, from Proto-West Germanic *frek. Cognate with Dutch vrek, Icelandic frekur. Compare also English freak.
Cognate with Dutch vreugde, Low German Freid, Danish fryd, Swedish fröjd.

Inherited from Middle High German vriuntlich, vrūntlich, friuntlich, from Old High German friuntlīcho, friuntlīh from Proto-Germanic *frijōndlīkaz, equivalent to Freund +‎ -lich. Cognate with Dutch vriendelijk, English friendly.
From Middle High German vorhtebære. Equivalent to Furcht +‎ -bar.
From Middle High German gedultic, from Old High German gidultig; By surface analysis, Geduld +‎ -ig. Cognates include Dutch geduldig and Old English geþyldig.
From Middle High German gevallen, from Old High German gifallan.[1] Equivalent to ge- (expressing the terminative aspect) +‎ fallen.
From Middle High German grōȥ, from Old High German grōȥ, akin to Old Saxon grōt, compare Dutch groot. More at English great.
Nominalization of  groß.
From Middle High German hazzen, from Old High German hazzōn, from Proto-Germanic *hatāną.
Cognate with Dutch klein and English clean. Doublet of  clean. For a similar semantic development, cf. zierlich (orig. "decorative", today "petite").

In Upper German dialects, the final [k]-sound after a long vowel was naturally interpreted as underlying /ɡ/. This form then also spread back northwards, though some northern Central German dialects (like Ripuarian) retained /k/, as did Low German.

Early 16th century in the sense “comedic”, directly from Latin comicus + -isch, from Ancient Greek κωμικός (kōmikós). The broader sense “funny” since the 17th century under influence of French comique. The sense “strange” was derived thence (as in English funny).

From Middle High German kurz, from Old High German kurz, from Proto-West Germanic *kurt, from Latin curtus. Compare also native Old High German *skurz, scurz and Middle High German schurz. Cognate with Dutch and Low German kort, English curt, Swedish kort.
From Middle High German lūt, from Old High German lūt, akin to Old Saxon hlūd, from Proto-West Germanic *hlūd.
From an earlier lockicht, from Middle High German lockeht, analyzable as Locke (“curl”) +‎ -ig.
From Middle High German lustec, from Old High German lustīg. By surface analysis, Lust (“pleasure, joy; wish”) +‎ -ig (“-y”).
From Middle Dutch net (“neat, decent, pretty”), from Old French net (“neat, decent”), from Latin nitidus. Compare English neat.

The form is unusual as it shows unshifted p-, but shifted -ch, even though the shift of initial p- to pf- occurred later than that of postvocalic -k to -ch. Theodor Frings therefore considered that the word was at first restricted to West Central German along the Rhine (which lacks the pf-shift) and only spread to Upper German slightly later when the shift was no longer active. (Middle High German pfich occurs only once in a Central German text from the 14th century and is thus probably a hypercorrection.)
Cognates include Danish rig, Dutch rijk, English rich, Icelandic ríkur Swedish rik and Plautdietsch rikj.

From Middle High German semfte, senfte, sanfte, from Old High German semfti, from Proto-West Germanic *samft(ī) (compare Proto-Germanic *sōmiz (“agreeable, fitting”)), from Proto-Indo-European *sóm-tu-, possibly from *sem- (“one, whole”).[1] Doublet of  sacht. Cognate with English soft.
From Middle High German sat, from Old High German sat, from Proto-West Germanic *sad, from Proto-Germanic *sadaz, from Proto-Indo-European *seh₂-. Compare Dutch zat, English sad, Danish sat.
From Middle High German sūber, from Old High German sūbar, from Proto-West Germanic *sūbrī, from Latin sobrius (“sober”).

From Middle High German scharpf, from Old High German scarf, from Proto-West Germanic *skarp, from Proto-Germanic *skarpaz, from Proto-Indo-European *(s)kerb-, from *(s)ker- (“to cut”). Compare Low German scharp, Dutch scherp, English sharp, Danish skarp.
From French chic, itself from German Schick (“correct manners, correct clothing”).
From Middle High German slanc, Middle Low German slank, ultimately related to Proto-Germanic *slingwaną (“to twist, wind”), the source of schlingen.
From Schmutz +‎ -ig, whence also dialectal Dutch smotsig. Compare also English smutty.
From Middle High German starc, from Old High German stark, from Proto-West Germanic *stark.

From Middle High German strenge, from Old High German strengi (“strong”), strangi, from Proto-Germanic *strangijaz (“tight, tense”), *strangaz, from Proto-Indo-European *strengʰ- (“taut”); related to Proto-Indo-European *ster- (“stiff”). Cognate with Dutch streng, English strong, Danish streng.

From Middle High German tōt, from Old High German tōt, from Proto-West Germanic *daud, from Proto-Germanic *daudaz. Compare Dutch dood, Middle Low German dôt, English dead, Danish død, Norwegian Nynorsk daud.

From Middle High German trūrec, from Old High German trūrag, from Proto-Germanic *dreuzagaz (“bloody”), from Proto-Indo-European *dʰreus- (“to break, break off, crumble”). Cognate with Dutch treurig (“sad, gloomy”), Low German trurig (“sad”), Hunsrik traurich (“sad”), English dreary (“grievous, dire, appalling, drab, dark, colourless, cheerless”), Old Norse dreyrigr (“bloody”).
un- (“un-”) +‎ ordentlich (“tidy”)
From Middle High German anzuc, verbal noun of aneziehen. Equivalent to an- +‎ Zug.
Borrowed from French blouse.
From Middle High German *halskette, from Old High German halsketinna (“neck shackle”). Equivalent to Hals (“neck”) +‎ Kette (“chain”); cognate with Dutch halsketting.

Inherited from Middle High German hantschuoch, from Old High German hantscuoh, from Proto-West Germanic *handuskōh. Equivalent to Hand (“hand”) +‎ Schuh (“shoe”). Cognate with Bavarian Håndschuach, German Low German Handsch, Handschoh, Hansch, Luxembourgish Händsch, Dutch handschoen, Danish handske, Norwegian Bokmål hanske, Norwegian Nynorsk hanske, handske (obsolete), Swedish handske, Faroese handski, Icelandic hanski, hanzki (obsolete).
From Hand (“hand”) +‎ Tasche (“bag”).
From Middle High German hemde, hemede, from Old High German hemidi (“skin”), from Proto-West Germanic *hamiþi (“shirt”).
From Middle High German hose, from Old High German hosa, from Proto-West Germanic *hosā.

From Middle High German kleit, from Old High German *kleid, from Proto-Germanic *klaiþą, from Proto-Indo-European *gleyt-. Cognate with Dutch kleed, Low German Kleid, English cloth. Possibly related to klettern, Klette, Klei.
From Middle High German venster, from Old High German fenstar, from Proto-West Germanic *fenestr (“window”).

From Middle High German küssen, from Old High German kussīn, from Proto-West Germanic *kussīn (“cushion, pillow”). The form Kissen with dialectal unrounding was standardised to avoid homophony with küssen (“to kiss”).
From Middle High German [Term?], from Old High German pflanza, borrowed from Latin planta. Cognate with Hunsrik and Luxembourgish Planz. Doublet of  Clan.

vocabList.definition:
cabinet , or :
cupboard 
wardrobe, closet 
bookcase
vocabList.etym: From Late Middle High German schranc, from Old High German scranc, from Proto-West Germanic *skrank, from Proto-Germanic *skrankaz (“grid, barrier”), probably derived from Proto-Indo-European *(s)ker- (“to bend, turn”).[1] Cognate with German Low German Schrank (“barrier, barricade”).
Cognate with Dutch stoel, English stool, Swedish stol; ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *steh₂- and thus related to stehen.
From Middle High German tisch, from Old High German tisc, from Proto-West Germanic *disk (“dish”).

From Middle High German want, from Old High German want, from Proto-Germanic *wanduz (“weave; wickerwork; plait; fence, wall”), from Proto-Indo-European *wendʰ- (“to turn; bend; wind; twist; braid; weave”). Cognate with English wand although developing a completely distinct meaning.
From Middle High German varwe, from Old High German farawa, from Proto-West Germanic *faru, from Proto-Germanic *farwō.

The form gelb is derived from the Middle High German inflected stem (as in herb), while the variant gehl is from the uninflected stem and from dialects that reduce -lw- to -l- in all positions (as in fahl, kahl). It survives in set phrases. Cognate with Dutch geel, Low German geel, English yellow.

From Middle High German hel (“resounding, loud, shining, bright”), from Old High German hel (“resounding”), from Proto-Germanic *halliz (“resounding”), from Proto-Germanic *hellaną (“to resound, make a sound”), from Proto-Indo-European *kelh₁- (“to call, make noise”). Cognate with Dutch hel.

vocabList.definition: to address informally using the pronoun du, to thou
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German duzen, dutzen, dützen, from Old High German *dūzzen, *dūezzen, equivalent to du +‎ -zen. Compare Middle English thouten.

From Middle High German echt, borrowed from Middle Low German echt (“lawful, genuine”). The original form is Middle Low German ēhaft (“lawful”), from ē (“law”) (related to modern Ehe); then ēhacht by the Low German development -ft- → -cht- (compare Nichte); and eventually contracted into echt. Cognate to Old High German ēhaft (“honourable”) and Dutch echt.

From Middle High German semfte, senfte, sanfte, from Old High German semfti, from Proto-West Germanic *samft(ī) (compare Proto-Germanic *sōmiz (“agreeable, fitting”)), from Proto-Indo-European *sóm-tu-, possibly from *sem- (“one, whole”).[1] Doublet of  sacht. Cognate with English soft.
Schub (“push”) +‎ Lade (“box”), 16th century.
zu- +‎ nehmen
From Middle High German lëben and Old High German lebēn, from Proto-West Germanic *libbjan, from Proto-Germanic *libjaną, from Proto-Indo-European *leyp- (“leave, cling, linger”).
Borrowed from English tank. The reflexive use is from the now archaic sense "tank, armoured vehicle".
From dr- +‎ außen; the first component is from a short form of dar-.
From Middle High German ecke, from Old High German egga, from Proto-West Germanic *aggju, from Proto-Germanic *agjō. Compare English edge.
From Middle High German richtunge, from Old High German rihtunga, from Proto-West Germanic *rihtungu. By surface analysis, richten +‎ -ung.
From Middle High German wīt, from Old High German wīt, from Proto-Germanic *wīdaz. Compare Low German wied, Hunsrik weid, Dutch wijd, English wide, Danish vid.
bauen (“build”) +‎ Stelle (“place”)

From Middle High German bewegen, from Old High German biwegan, from Proto-West Germanic *biwegan, derived from Proto-Germanic *weganą (“to move”),[1] which stems from Proto-Indo-European *weǵʰ-. Compare English beweigh.
Inherited from Middle High German spil(e)n, from Old High German spilōn, from Proto-West Germanic *spilōn.
From Middle High German ëzzen, from Old High German ezzan, akin to Old Saxon etan, compare Dutch eten.
From Middle High German sat, from Old High German sat, from Proto-West Germanic *sad, from Proto-Germanic *sadaz, from Proto-Indo-European *seh₂-. Compare Dutch zat, English sad, Danish sat.
From Middle High German geschenke, equivalent to ge- +‎ schenken.

From Middle High German zaln, zalen, from Old High German zalōn, from Proto-West Germanic *talōn, from Proto-Germanic *talōną (“to tell, recount; to count, reckon”). Cognate with Bavarian zoin, English tale, Dutch talen, Swedish tala, Danish tal. Equivalent to Zahl +‎ -en.

From Middle High German drucken, from Old High German drucchen, drukken, from Proto-West Germanic *þrukkijan (“to press”). Doublet of  drücken (“to press, push”) with Upper German lack of umlaut before a velar geminate; the first German printers were in the south. Established as technical term for printing in the 17th century (see also bedrucken).

vocabList.definition:
to propose, to advise in favor of
 to recommend
vocabList.etym: Related to German befehlen (“command, order”), but not fehlen (“to be missing”).

vocabList.definition: drum set, drum kit, drums, percussion
vocabList.etym: Ca. 1900, from schlagen (“to beat”) +‎ Zeug (“equipment”).
fernsehen +‎ -er
From Middle High German sehen, from Old High German sehan, from Proto-West Germanic *sehwan.
Borrowed from French passer. Compare English pass.
From Middle High German snīen, from Old High German snīwan, from Proto-West Germanic *snīwan, from Proto-Germanic *snīwaną.
From Late Middle High German koffer, from Middle Dutch coffer, from Old French cofre.
From Middle High German urloup. Related to erlauben. Cognate with English leave (“time off, permission to be away”).
From Middle High German behandeln (“to touch with the hand”), equivalent to be- +‎ handeln. Compare Saterland Frisian behondelje, Dutch behandelen, English behandle.
behandeln +‎ -ung
15th century, equivalent to regieren (“to reign”) +‎ -ung.

vocabList.definition: to lose one’s way/ to get lost

vocabList.etym: From lang (“long”, adjective) +‎ Weile (“while”, noun). Cognate with Hunsrik langweilich.
From Middle High German lernen, from Old High German lernēn, lirnēn, from Proto-West Germanic *liʀnēn. Cognate with Old English leornian (Modern English learn). Related to lehren.

vocabList.definition: to be silent / to say nothing

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German wort. Compare Dutch woord, English word, Danish ord. Doublet of  Verb.
From Middle High German [Term?]. Deverbal from  berufen (literally “calling”).

From Middle High German gehalt, deverbal from gehalten (“to keep still, retain, preserve, imprison”), itself from halten (“to hold”). The earliest attested sense of the noun is “custody, prison”. In some southern dialects it also means “room, container, closet”. The modern sense develops in the 15th century, at first in the context of coins and metal alloys.
From Middle High German kochen, from Old High German kohhōn, from Proto-West Germanic *kokōn (“to cook”).
From Middle High German gelegenheit. By surface analysis, gelegen +‎ -heit.

vocabList.definition: long, a long while, a while, for long, for a long time
to exhibit, make public, show clearly

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German zimber, from Old High German zimbar, from Proto-West Germanic *timr, from Proto-Germanic *timrą, from Proto-Indo-European *dem- (“build, house”) (see Proto-Indo-European *dṓm). Cognate with English timber and Dutch timmer (“building; construction; room”).
From fūcus (“seaweed, orchil, pretense”) +‎ -ō.
From the root of celer, from Proto-Indo-European *kel- (“to drive, force to move quickly”).

From Proto-Italic *weneznom (“lust, desire”), from Proto-Indo-European *wenh₁- (“to strive, wish, love”). See also Sanskrit वनति (vanati, “gain, wish, erotic lust”), Latin Venus, veneror, venia, vēnor and English wish.

vocabList.definition: to tell, to narrate, to recount
vocabList.etym: From Middle High German erzellen, from Old High German irzellen. Equivalent to er- +‎ zählen.

vocabList.definition:
to remind From Middle High German er- +‎ innern from Old High German innarōn (“make someone perceive inwardly”), from innar (“inner”), see the preposition in (“in”).
,second-person singular present of erinnern

vocabList.etym: From Middle High German īlen, from Old High German īlen, from Proto-West Germanic *īlijan (“to make haste, hasten”).
